🚀 Step 6 — Create Dockerfile

Inside kutu-app folder:

nano Dockerfile

✅ Step 6.1 — FROM

Add this first:

FROM node:18

🔍 What it means

Every Docker image starts with a base image
Here we are using:

Node.js version 18

Equivalent to:

Ubuntu + Node.js already installed

✅ Step 6.2 — ARG

Add this below:

ARG VERSION=1.0

🔍 What is ARG?

ARG = build-time variable

Used during:

docker build

NOT runtime.

Example

Later you can build like:

docker build --build-arg VERSION=2.0 -t kutu-app .

✅ Step 6.3 — WORKDIR

Add:

WORKDIR /app

🔍 What it does

Inside container:

/app

becomes the working directory.

Equivalent to:

cd /app

✅ Step 6.4 — COPY

Add:

COPY package.json .

🔍 Meaning

Copies:

package.json

from your local machine → container /app

✅ Step 6.5 — RUN

Add:

RUN npm install

🔍 Meaning

Executes command during image build.

Here:

npm install

installs Express dependency.

✅ Step 6.6 — Copy Remaining Files

Add:

COPY . .

🔍 Meaning

Copies everything into container:

server.js
views/
other files

✅ Step 6.7 — ENV

Add:

ENV NODE_ENV=production
ENV PORT=3000

🔍 Meaning

Environment variables inside container.

Your app already uses:

process.env.PORT
process.env.NODE_ENV

So Docker injects values.

✅ Step 6.8 — EXPOSE

Add:

EXPOSE 3000

🔍 Meaning

Documents that container uses:

port 3000

⚠️ Important:
EXPOSE does NOT publish port automatically.

Still need:

-p 3000:3000

during run.

✅ Step 6.9 — CMD

Add final line:

CMD ["npm", "start"]

🔍 Meaning

Default command when container starts.

Equivalent to:

npm start

✅ Final Dockerfile

You should now have:

FROM node:18

ARG VERSION=1.0

WORKDIR /app

COPY package.json .

RUN npm install

COPY . .

ENV NODE_ENV=production
ENV PORT=3000

EXPOSE 3000

CMD ["npm", "start"]

🚀 Step 7 — Build Docker Image

Run:

docker build -t kutu-app .

🚀 Step 8 — Run Container

Run:

docker run -d --name kutu-container -p 3000:3000 kutu-app
